<review>This coffee shop is not only a caf√©...  But a local La Jolla institution!

It is a great place for a well deserved break in your busy schedule, to sit, lounge, and relax... or simply to pick up a delicious goody to eat or drink.

Located in the commercial district of LJ, and very near to the not to be missed La Jolla Cove Park, you can then do some strolling, shopping, and then finish your afternoon immersing yourself in the boundless natural beauty of this park!

We highly recommend Pannikin for sure! Stop by to relax and enjoy!< /review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPvXHeWbmrP9ZXCoT7U3JLAygJALCw8yOqPXMxA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOpZkUm7stVFmiUZ9S-i3HVcNWzX-PbxjYSePxJ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPnmw3gMBjU-C4_01ljh_F8TGVaI2dSMtqRWi9I=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNkyvnomPkoRfkF9x_iHrbTaZ10QkUP9M43P1ai=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPJzCVlAecHslMmq7FK4YDERLY8OVUJZD0hPx9z=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>< response>

< text>
So this place used to be cool, but about a month ago we came back after sometime and my Girlfriend ordered a Sandwhich after reading that it had egg and cheese after the sandwhich came it was only a veggie sandwhich. We thought it was strange and that maybe we did ask for it.

Second part: today I came to Pannikin with some friends that where visiting the area, we all ordered burritos, and to the surprise of us out of 4 burritos each one had a diferent build: one had eggs inside (did not mention or ask for it as the menu said), second one had veggies, third one had veggies and beans (not asked for),and mine was also a veggie burrito and got charged for beans and papas, so it shows a lack of coordination.

We will not return after coming here for the past 15 years, this place fell off.</text>

<UserId.>103390742398477982098</UserId.><user_name>Tyler Anneliese Moselle< /user_name>< time>
1412018382808</time>
< rating>
5< /rating>
< review>
Pannikin has lost a few locations, but the owners of the La Jolla location have really invested time and love into maintaining the character of this cult favorite. I can't tell you how many of my childhood weekend mornings started here, checking the classifieds over hot chocolate (now the house blend or a "hammerhead" will do!) and chatting with locals... including a few Padres players over the years! The chess board, the gigantic carrot cake cupcakes behind the case, and tempting soups and Mexican breakfast items are often the only things I missed while living abroad or while suffering through my college years in LA. If you really want the full story on why I love this place you'll have to meet me, but in my mind, Pannikin is an institution and a family favorite that can do no wrong. My late mother's ashes are here and I will always find an excuse to enjoy a buzz with the resident sparrows as long as I live.<//review>

<pictures>None< /pictures><review>I feel so offended coming here after having amazing breakfast burritos in Colorado. The tortilla was cold and dry, no warming up done whatsoever. The potatoes inside were mashed instead of being "house roasted" like I was told. Seriously - who puts mashed potatoes in a burrito? The eggs were average, just some eggs. Avocado was just that, avocado. The cheese was cheddar, which doesn't belong on a breakfast burrito. And to top it all off, no seasoning was used anywhere in the burrito. It seems like there should more options for meat other than bacon, maybe sausage? Chorizo? Those are staples in breakfast burritos in Colorado. This seems like a burrito I would've made in middle school thinking it would be good but then realizing later how awful it was.

The coffee was alright, I had a cortado and I can't say I absolutely loved it or hated it.< /review></record>

We haven't been in the area for a while so it was good to drop by for cappuccinos and a light lunch.It's always pretty crowded on Sundays around midday but you never wait long to get service.We got our coffees and a ham panwich on sourdough to share.It was nice to sit out the front on the patio and enjoy the atmosphere.The cappuccinos were pretty good and the sandwich was okay...their sourdough here is the same as the one at the Encinitas location....very dry,almost stale.I don't know why they don't use fresh ciabattas or something.The choice is sourdough or wholewheat only.We'll remember not to order a sandwich next time we are here otherwise everything is fine.<//Text>

5</Rate>
<Text>Taco Tuesday!

Wife and I stopped here for lunch on Tuesday about 12:30.

Had a nice table on the patio in the shade  out of the warm weather.  The waiter brought us thick chips and a thick salsa. Mmm, they are good, he brought mitre later.

It was taco Tuesday with a special additional menus, $3 tacos and a $4 large taco. $1.50 for guacamole and $8.00 for an 18 oz margarita.

We each had the large and I had a margarita. One taco was plenty big and tasted great. The margarita was good, with ice cubes and salt. It was $20 for the whole meal.

Service was good, they inquired several times how we were doing.< /Text>< pics>

Many restaurants claim to treat you like family but this one actually delivers on that promise.  The food has been consistently delicious for at the 35 years that I've been eating there and qhen they moved to Solana Beach they brought the original food and mellow vibe with them from La Jolla.  Despite their success, the owner remain very much present and truly embidies the word host.
The descor is warm and welcoming.  It's not fancy and they don't change the menu to follow the trend of the latest trends, but they start with good ingredients and know how to use them to create classic dishes like camarones mojo de ajo and sauteed fajitas, dishes that very few places do well anymore.
if you're not local, it's three minutes from the 5 to Highway 101, so why not pull off the Freeway and pull up a chair.  You won't regret it.<//Review>

<Time>1489689719673<//Time>< gmap_id>
0x80dc0ed390400041:0x92d7faa71175fab9</gmap_id>
<Response>None< /Response>< review>
I frequent here a lot as my SO's mother loves dining here. I am not a huge fan. Friendly service from the wait staff and on point. They accept reservations and the best place to sit is on the patio and not too close to the one man band station. Yes, they do have live music for you to enjoy.

They really need to work on some of their dishes though the queso fundido is served on a plate and sprinkles of chorizo, you can def provide more than that for the mark up on your meals. It would be much tastier in skillet or deeper dish to easily scoop up the queso. One night I ordered a Cali burrito, it tasted like it was previously frozen and microwaved, the fries was tough, cold, and disgusting. I had other dishes there, but don't remember because not as memorable.

The best dish so far I had there was the Steak Ranchero. I would get that again and just stick to what I know is good next time.

I don't really recommend this place unless you're going with friends and family that are footing the bill and love this place. I would rather go to a hole in the wall taco shop south of San Diego.</review>

<Pics>None</Pics><UserId.>110530732671928110124</UserId.>< Text>
Much, much cleaner and better stocked than the majority of the dollar trees in San Jose.

It's not completely wheelchair accessible, they still have many boxes in the aisles, but it is at least navigable in a wheelchair.

This is pretty quiet location, rarely see many other customers while shopping. I go to all the dollar trees in the area, frequently.

This location is fairly large. It's slightly smaller than the one on union, but bigger than many, such as the one on Winchester.

There is a frozen section. Most items are standard, you will see them at every dollar tree. Lots of seasonal/holiday items in the front. Party supplies, cleaning supplies, greeting cards, makeup, toiletries, housewares, candy and snacks.</Text>

< Review>
Likely the best Mexican restaurant in Fairfield - everything is delicious!  Street tacos, tortas, tostadas, horchata... the menu is large, and many menu items have a unique twist.  You can fit the family (it's larger than it looks from the outside), but if you come at the busiest times you may have a harder time finding a seat.  This place is popular with Hispanics.</Review>

<resp>None< /resp>< Text>
Dr. Kevin Barry was recommended to me by a friend who has been his patient for over 20 years. On my first visit he spotted what turned out to be a root canal emergency (completely overlooked by previous dentist). He set up an appointment with a root canal specialist 2 blocks away who did the surgery that afternoon. Dr. K. Barry has the latest technology and the expertise/experience to match. He's the best dentist I've ever had, and I'm pretty old (60+). He's a lover of small talk, which puts me at ease during procedures. Always has a smile on his face and is willing to help. I've never seen him have a negative interaction with anyone. His staff will bend over backwards to set you up with a convenient appointment. They are excellent communicators (text, email, etc.)  Covid guidelines are in place. Dr. Barry also knows a network of highly competent dentists of various specialties to recommend for additional work you may need, which is a Plus in any profession! The best...A++ 8 years and still impressed!<//Text>

< review>
First of all, they're in the beautiful, Pflueger-designed, easy-to-get-to 450 Sutter building, which makes going in a pleasure in itself.  But the staff and Dr. Barry (Dan) are what makes the place so wonderful.  Unlike many other dental offices, they have always called me in from the lobby the moment my appointment time arrived--no waiting because other patients were late or due to overbooking.  The hygienists are all friendly and thorough.  Dr. Barry does excellent work and is a real card.  The administrative staff are very friendly and know their work; they never seem puzzled or confused or otherwise unable to figure out billing and insurance stuff--like other offices I've been to.  Definitely recommend!< /review>

<user_id>116320705424847663337<//user_id><user_name>Pat Huey<//user_name><Date>1568130645207< /Date>< rating>
5< /rating>
<text>I have bruxism (tooth grinding) and Dr Daniel Barry gave me the perfect solution: sleep on your back. That way your neck and jaw relax and it eliminates the problem of grinding. He said when you sleep on your side, your neck is at an angle and this adds stress to it, which can trigger the bruxism. He also suggested a yogic breathing exercise (pranayama), and a couple of other non-druggie suggestions. (If you do yoga, a supported shoulder stand, which Mr Iyengar called the mother of all asanas, is excellent for anxiety and sleep problems.) What other dentist would come up with these kinds of suggestions? I wish I had known about them years ago. I've been doing them and sleep much better, and I am pretty sure that I'm no longer grinding at night.

He did an implant and two crowns for me (both resulting from the horrid bruxism) and did a perfect job. One of the crowns was put in by another dentist who had not done a great job (in fact, I'm pretty sure it was unnecessary, and it only lasted two years) and he did a great job working around the problems the bad dentist had caused. The mouth guard I bought fits perfectly.

The staff are always pleasant, cheerful, and competent.

My friend who recommended the Barrys has been going to them for 27 years. I wish I had known about them 27 years ago!<//text>< pictures>
None</pictures>

I especially appreciate his interest and engagement in his work. As he was showing me my X-rays, several times he noted something and said, "Isn't that interesting?" And that extended to other physical concerns. Dr. Barry understands how dental health relates to the rest of the body, something most dentists never talk about. I'm so glad to have found him and highly recommend him and the whole office.<//text>

<user_name>Tom K</user_name><date>1436059325482<//date>< pictures>

< review>
My wife and I were looking for a Toy Hauler and did plenty of research as this was our first trailer. We dealt with a couple of other dealerships prior to going to Major. We were specific with our price point and what we wanted. We were told they could work on the price. After driving for hours, we found out this wasn't the case. In addition to no flexibility, the wanted to charge thousands of dollars for "PDI" and heavily "marked up" the price for the battery as well as the sway bar/weight distribution system. After almost giving up, I contacted Major through email. I was answered promptly by Jeremy. He advised that the price listed was the lowest they could do. This was refreshing, as I knew the price going into it and didn't stress about having to "haggle." He gave a full breakdown of out the door pricing, in writing.  After looking at the price quote and comparing to other dealerships, I found their price to be better than anywhere else I looked. The only issue I ran into was after driving an hour and a half on a Sunday to look at the trailer, Jeremy told me their financing was closed and we would have to wait till Monday. He called back on Monday and advised us the financing went through and we could pick it up. We went on a Friday, which was Jeremy's day off, and met with Brandon who did the walk through. He was very thorough and provided helpful tips. While doing the walk through, Jeremy showed up to congratulate us and make sure everything was in order. April made the paperwork process a breeze and we were out the door. Overall I am very happy with the service provided. The staff was very helpful and I never felt pressured into buying. They didn't "hover" over us as we were looking around, but were available for assistance when needed. I would definitely refer them to anyone wanting to buy a RV.<//review>

<Text>Bought a new 2014 Salem Cruise Lite travel trailer.  Anthony was my sales person and was patient with me throughout the entirety of the sale.  Their prices were the lowest around so they didn't really negotiate on price (just a couple hundred) and I scoured the trailer before taking delivery and found a few minor issues which they addressed immediately.  I mean, I really checked everything using a checklist I found online.  He didn't rush me during the PDI and walked me through the trailer showing me how everything works, which is standard practice, but was nice anyway.  They also set up my weight distribution equipment on the trailer while I was inspecting the trailer.  I passed on their aftermarket warranty and recommend instead getting the 2nd year warranty direct from Forest River for $150 (or $250 depending on model).

I did end up having an issue with the floor during the first outing and the service department was spot on coordinating the repair with Forest River in Rialto and I got my trailer back in no time.  I was upset that the linoleum floor needed to be replaced, but that wasn't the dealer's fault and they were great with the warranty coverage.  The lesson here is to check the floor with your BARE FEET, not just shoes. ;)

It's a small RV dealer and overall a first class operation, I recommend.<//Text><response>None< /response>< GmapID>
